mporain | year=1954 | volume =4-5 | pages = 303\u2013312 | location = Athens | language=French| ref=refZakythinos1954}}\n* {{Cite book| first1=Alvise| last1=Zorzi| title=Venice, 697-1797: city, republic, empire| publisher=Sidgwick & Jackson| year=1983| isbn=0-283-98984-X| url=https://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN028398984X| ref=refZorzi1983| accessdate=10 August 2011}}\n* {{Cite book| first=| last=Foreign Office of Great Britain| title=Correspondence respecting the demands made upon the Greek Government; and respecting the Islands of Cervi and Sapienza: presented to both Houses of Parliament by Command of Her Majesty| publisher=Harrison and Son| year=1850| isbn=| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XU1BAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Correspondence+respecting+the+demands+made+upon+the+Greek+Government;+and+respecting+the+Islands+of+Cervi+and+Sapienza:+presented+to+both+Houses+of+Parliament+by+Command+of+Her+Majesty#v=onepage&q&f=false| ref=refForeignOffice1850| accessdate=10 August 2011}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{History of the Ionian Islands|state=expanded}}\n{{Republic of Venice}}\n{{Stato da Mar}}\n\n[[Category:Venetian rule in the Ionian Islands| ]]\n[[Category:Stato da M\u00e0r]]\n[[Category:1797 disestablishments in the Republic of Venice|Ionian Islands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox Former subdivision\n|native_name            = ''{{lang|vec|Ixo\u0142e Jonie}}'' <br />{{lang|el|\u1f38\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9\u03bf\u03b9 \u039d\u1fc6\u03c3\u03bf\u03b9}}\n|conventional_long_name = Ionian Islands\n|common_name            = Ionian Islands\n|\n|image_flag             = Flag of the Republic of Venice.svg\n|flag                   = Flag of Veneto\n|flag_type              = \n|image_coat             = Venetian colonial emblem (coin).svg\n|image_map              = William Faden. Composite Mediterranean. 1785.R.jpg\n|image_map_caption      = The Ionian Islands in green. Map of 1785, when the Islands were still part of the [[Venetian Republic]].\n|\n|nation                 = the [[Republic of Venice]]\n|subdivision            = Colony\n|era                    = Middle Ages\n|capital                = [[Corfu (city)|Corfu]]\n|today                  = {{flag|Greece}}\n|year_start             = 1363\n|event_pre              = Fourth Crusade\n|date_pre               = 1202\u20131204\n|event_start            = Established{{smallsup|1}}\n|event1                 = [[Ottoman\u2013Venetian War (1463\u20131479)|First Ottoman\u2013Venetian War]]\n|date_event1            = 1463\u20131479\n|event2                 = [[Ottoman\u2013Venetian War (1499\u20131503)|Second Ottoman\u2013Venetian War]]\n|date_event2            = 1499\u20131503\n|event3                 = [[Treaty of Passarowitz]]\n|date_event3            = 1718\n|event_end              = [[War of the First Coalition|Invasion of Venice]]\n|date_end               = 1792\u2013\n|year_end               = 1797\n|event_post             = Treaty of Campo Formio\n|date_post              = 17 October 1797\n|\n|p1              = Kingdom of Naples\n|flag_p1         = Flag of the Kingdom of Naples.svg\n|p2              = Ottoman Empire\n|flag_p2         = Flag of the Ottoman Empire.svg\n|s1              = French rule in the Ionian Islands (1797\u20131799)\n|flag_s1         = Flag of France.svg\n|\n|footnotes              = {{Smallsup|1}} Each island became part of the Venetian empire in different dates. 1363 refers to Cythera and Anticythera.\n}}\n{{History of Greece}}\n\nThe [[Ionian Islands]] were an overseas possession of the [[Republic of Venice]] from the mid-14th century until the late 18th century. The conquest of the islands took place gradually. The first to be acquired was [[Kythira|Cythera]] and the neighboring islet of [[Antikythera|Anticythera]], indirectly in 1238 and directly after 1363. In 1386, [[Corfu]] voluntarily became part of Venice's colonies. Following a century, Venice captured [[Zakynthos|Zante]] in 1485, [[Cephalonia]] in 1500 and [[Ithaca]] in 1503. The conquest was completed in 1718 with the capture of [[Lefkada]]. Each of the islands remained part of the Venetian ''[[Stato da M\u00e0r]]'' until [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] dissolved the Republic of Venice in 1797, annexing Corfu. The Ionian Islands are situated in the Ionian Sea, off the west coast of [[Geography of Greece|Greece]]. Cythera, the southernmost, is just off the southern tip of the [[Peloponnese]] and Corfu, the northernmost, is located at the entrance of the [[Adriatic Sea]]. In modern Greek, the period of Venetian rule over Greek territory is known as ''Venetokratia'' or ''Enetokratia'' ({{lang-el|\u0392\u03b5\u03bd\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03af\u03b1}} or {{lang|el|\u0395\u03bd\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03af\u03b1}}) and literally means \"rule of the Venetians\".<ref>[[#refBrameSaportaContrerasNewmeyer1986|Brame, Saporta, Contreras & Newmeyer]], p.&nbsp;213.</ref> It is believed that the Venetian period on the Ionian Islands was agreeable, especially compared with the coinciding ''Tourkokratia'' \u2014 [[Ottoman_Greece|Turkish rule]] over the remainder of present-day Greece.<ref>[[#refTsitselis1960|Tsitselis]], p.&nbsp;529.</ref>\n\nThe governor of the Ionian Islands during the Venetian period was the ''[[Provveditore generale da Mar]]'', who resided on [[Corfu (city)|Corfu]]. Additionally, each island's authorities were divided into the Venetian and the domestic authorities. The economy of the islands was based on exporting local goods, primarily [[raisin]]s, [[olive oil]] and [[wine]], whereas [[Venetian lira]], the currency of Venice, was also the currency of the islands. Some features of the culture of Venice were incorporated in the culture of the Ionian Islands, thus influencing to this day local music, cuisine and language.  The [[Italian language]], for instance, which was introduced on the islands as the official language and was adopted by the upper class, is still popular today throughout the islands.\n\n== Relations between Venice and Byzantium ==\n[[File:Venice, by Bolognino Zaltieri, 1565.jpg|thumb|220px|right|View of Venice in 1565]]\nVenice was founded in 421 after the destruction of nearby communities by the [[Huns]] and the [[Lombards]]. In the shifting Italian borders of the following centuries, Venice benefited from remaining under the control of the [[Roman Empire]] - increasingly as the furtherest Northwestern outpost of the now [[Constantinople]] centered power.  During [[Justinian I]]'s reconquest of Italy from the Visigoths, Venice was an increasingly important stronghold for the Empire's [[Exarchate of Ravenna]].<ref>[[#refThiriet1975|Thiriet]], p.&nbsp;32.</ref> The political centre of the exarchate, and the most senior military officials of the Empire, were situated in [[Ravenna]].<ref>[[#refMauskopfDeliyannis2009|Mauskopf Deliyannis]], p.&nbsp;278.</ref><ref>[[#refGraftonMostSettis2010|Grafton, Most & Settis]], p.&nbsp;806.</ref> The subordinate military officials who were their representatives in the [[Venetian Lagoon|Venetian lagoons]] were called tribunes, and only in about AD 697 were the lagoons made a separate military command under a ''{{lang|la|dux}}'' ({{lang|vec|[[doge]]}}).<ref>[[#refLane1973|Lane]], p.&nbsp;4.</ref> Notwithstanding the election of the first {{lang|vec|[[Doge of Venice|Doge]]}}, vassalic evidence such as honours and orders received by the doge from the [[List of Byzantine emperors|Emperor]] implies that Venice was considered part of the Byzantine Empire even after the capture of Ravenna by the Lombards.<ref name=\"Lane5\">[[#refLane1973|Lane]], p.&nbsp;5.</ref> Despite the {{lang|la|[[Pax Nicephori]]}} (803), which recognised Venice as Byzantine territory, the influence of the Eastern Roman Emperor slowly faded away.<ref name=\"Lane5\" /> By 814 Venice functioned as a fully independent republic.<ref>[[#refLuttwak2009|Luttwak]], p.&nbsp;151.</ref> Even so, Venice became a partner of the Empire and trading privileges were granted to it by the Emperors via treaties,<ref>[[#refNicol1992|Nicol]], p.&nbsp;16.</ref> such as the [[Byzantine\u2013Venetian Treaty of 1082]].\n\nThe [[Fourth Crusade]] (1202\u20131204) was initially intended to invade Muslim-controlled areas; instead, the Crusaders attacked the capital of the Byzantine Empire, [[Constantinople]], resulting in the temporary dissolution of the empire and the [[sack of Constantinople|sack]] of its capital.<ref>[[#refLaiou2005|Laiou]], p.&nbsp;154.</ref> As Venice was one of the participants in the Crusade its relations with the Byzantine Empire were strained during this period.<ref name=\"Nicol66\">[[#refNicol1992|Nicol]], p.&nbsp;66.</ref> Moreover, by styling themselves \"Lord of one-quarter and one-eighth of the whole Empire of Romania\" after the Crusade, the Doges of Venice contributed to the deterioration of the relations between the two states.<ref name=\"Nicol66\"/><ref>[[#refNicol1992|Nicol]], p.&nbsp;254.</ref> Efforts to improve relations, for example through the [[Nicaean\u2013Venetian Treaty of 1219]], proved unsuccessful.<ref>[[#refNovoselova1971|Novoselova]], p.&nbsp;547.</ref> A period of friendly relations only followed the [[Sicilian Vespers]] in 1282, when Venice, foreseeing the fall of [[Charles I of Naples|Charles]], the French [[King of Sicily]], began forming closer relations with Byzantium.<ref name=NS599>[[#refNovoselova1971|Novoselova]], p.&nbsp;599.</ref> Venice had been bound by an alliance with Charles against Byzantium in 1281.<ref name=NS599/>\n\n== Appellation ==\n[[File:Venetian map of the castles of Corfu (1690).jpg|thumb|A {{circa|1690}} Venetian map of ''{{lang|it|Isola di Corfu : posseduta dalla Serenissima Republica di Venetia}}''. The map shows the fortresses of Corfu surrounded by wreaths and ribbons. {{lang|el-Latn|Angelokastro}} is indicated as \"{{lang|it|Castello S. Angelo}}\" in a ribbon below the top right wreath of the map.]]\nThe Islands were referred to, both individually and collectively, by various names. After Venice [[siege of the Castle of St. George|captured]] Cephalonia on 24 December 1500, the administration of the defense of all the islands was delegated to an official seated in Corfu. This official was being referred to as \"the General ''{{lang|it|[[Provveditore]]}}'' of the Three Islands\" (''{{lang|it|Provveditore Generale delle Tre Isole}}'') and resided at the fortress of [[Angelokastro (Corfu)|Angelokastro]] from 1387 to the end of the 16th century.<ref name=\"ASV5\">[[#refASV1937|Archivio di Stato di Venezia]], p.&nbsp;5.</ref> The ''Three Islands'' refer to Corfu, Zante and Cephalonia.<ref name=\"ASV5\"/> The Venetian equivalent for \"Ionian Islands\" is ''{{lang|vec|Ixo\u0142e Jonie}}'', the Italian being ''{{lang|it|Isole Ionie}}'' and the Greek {{lang|el|\u0399\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1 \u039d\u03b7\u03c3\u03b9\u03ac}} in [[Modern Greek]] and {{lang|grc|\u1f38\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9\u03bf\u03b9 \u039d\u1fc6\u03c3\u03bf\u03b9}} in {{lang|el-Latn|[[Katharevousa]]}}.\n\nBelow are the seven principal islands from north to south, including their Greek and Italian names in parentheses:\n\n* [[Corfu]] ({{lang|el-Latn|Kerkyra}}; {{lang|vec|Corf\u00f9}})<ref name=\"FMS44\">[[#refFr\u00e9chetMeghraouiStucchi2008|Fr\u00e9chet, Meghraoui & Stucchi]], p.&nbsp;44.</ref>\n* [[Paxos]] ({{lang|el-Latn|Paxi}}; {{lang|vec|Passo}})<ref>[[#refSmyth1854|Smyth]], p.&nbsp;53.</ref>\n* [[Lefkada]] ({{lang|el-Latn|Leucas}}; {{lang|vec|Santa Maura}} or {{lang|vec|L\u00e8ucade}})<ref name=\"FMS44\"/>\n* [[Cephalonia]] ({{lang|el-Latn|Kefal(l)onia}} or {{lang|el-Latn|Kefal(l)inia}}; {{lang|vec|Cefalonia}})<ref name=\"FMS44\"/>\n* [[Ithaca]] ({{lang|el-Latn|Ithaki}} or {{lang|el-Latn|Thiaki}}; {{lang|vec|Itaca}}, {{lang|vec|Val di Compare}} or {{lang|vec|Piccola Cefalonia}})<ref>[[#refSoreide2011|Soreide]], p.&nbsp;48.</ref>\n* [[Zante]] ({{lang|el-Latn|Zakynthos}}; {{lang|vec|Zante}} or {{lang|vec|Zacinto}})<ref name=\"FMS44\"/>, see [[History_of_Zakynthos#Venetian_rule_(1484\u20131797)|the long account here]]\n* [[Kythira|Cythera]] ({{lang|el-Latn|Kythira}}; {{lang|vec|Cerigo}})<ref>[[#refMacmillan1994|Macmillan]], p.&nbsp;84.</ref>\n\nCythera and Lefkada were additionally called ''{{lang|ota-Latn|\u00c7uha Adas\u0131}}'' or ''{{lang|ota-Latn|\u00c7uka Adas\u0131}}'' and ''{{lang|ota-Latn|Ayamavra}}'' respectively by the Ottomans.<ref>[[#refDaviesDavis2007|Davies & Davis]], p.&nbsp;37.</ref><ref>{{lang|la|[[#refAO2006|Archivum ottomanicum]]}}, p.&nbsp;240.</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Roman and Byzantine period ===\nDuring the Roman Empire, the Ionian Islands were variously part of the [[roman province|provinces]] of [[Achaea (Roman province)|Achaea]] and [[Epirus vetus]].<ref>[[#refKazhdan1991|Kazhdan]], p.&nbsp;1007.</ref> These would form, with the exception of Cythera, the [[Byzantine]] [[theme (Byzantine district)|theme]] of [[Cephallenia (theme)|Cephallenia]] in the late 8th century.<ref>[[#refZakythinos1954|Zakythinos]], p.&nbsp;529.</ref> From the late 11th century, the Ionian Islands became a battleground in the [[Byzantine\u2013Norman Wars]]. The island of Corfu was held by the Normans in 1081\u20131085 and 1147\u20131149, while the Venetians unsuccessfully besieged it in 1122\u20131123. The island of Cephalonia was also unsuccessfully besieged in 1085, but was plundered in 1099 by the [[Pisa]]ns and in 1126 by the Venetians.<ref>[[#refSoustalKoder1981|Soustal & Koder]], p.&nbsp;56\u201357, 176.</ref>  Finally, Corfu and the rest of the theme, except for Lefkada, were captured by the [[Normans]] under [[William II of Sicily]] in 1185. Although Corfu was recovered by the Byzantines by 1191, the other islands henceforth remained lost to Byzantium, and formed a [[County palatine of Cephalonia and Zakynthos]] under William's [[Greeks|Greek]] admiral [[Margaritus of Brindisi]].<ref>[[#refKazhdan1991|Kazhdan]], p.&nbsp;1123.</ref><ref>[[#refSoustalKoder1981|Soustal & Koder]], p.&nbsp;58, 176.</ref>\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin:0 0 1em 1em;\"\n| style=\"background:#ddd; text-align:center;\"|\n<div class=\"center\">\n; Count Palatine Dynasties of Cephalonia and Zakynthos\n</div>\n|-\n|\n<gallery>\nFile:Armoiries Anjou Durazzo.svg|Arms of the House of Anjou-Durazzo\nFile:Tocco stemma.svg|Arms of the family of [[Tocco family|Tocco]], the last rulers of the County\n</gallery>\n|}\n\n=== The ''{{lang|el-Latn|Frankokratia}}'' ===\nFollowing the Fourth Crusade and the signature of the ''{{lang|la|[[Partitio terrarum imperii Romaniae]]}}'', Corfu came under Venetian rule.<ref>[[#refHerrinSaint-Guillain2011|Herrin & Saint-Guillain]], p.&nbsp;82.</ref> In 1207 though, doge [[Pietro Ziani]] ceded the island as a ''{{lang|la|[[feudum]]}}'' to ten Venetian nobles, provided that they demonstrate loyalty and devotion and that they pay taxes.<ref>[[#refMiller1908|Miller]], p.&nbsp;88.</ref> Corfu passed in the hands of the [[Despotate of Epirus]] around 1214, and was captured in 1257 by [[Manfred of Sicily]], who put his [[admiral]] [[Philippe Chinard]] there in charge of his eastern possessions. Nonetheless, with the defeat of Manfred at [[Battle of Benevento|Benevento]] and the signature of the [[Treaty of Viterbo]] on 27 May 1267, Corfu became a possession of the [[Capetian House of Anjou|Angevin]] [[Kingdom of Naples]].<ref>[[#refNicol1992|Nicol]], p.&nbsp;401\u2013402.</ref> Meanwhile, the rest of the islands continued to form part of the County palatine,<ref>[[#refTsitselis1960|Tsitselis]], p.&nbsp;400.</ref><ref>[[#refMercati1811|Mercati]], p.&nbsp;17-18.</ref> which throughout its existence was governed by three families: the Orsini (whose relation to the Roman [[Orsini family]] is unattested<ref>Andreas Kiesewetter, ''Preludio alla Quarta Crociata? Megareites di Brindisi, Maio di Cefalonia e la signoria sulle isole ionie (1185-1250)'', in Gherardo Ortalli, Giorgio Ravegnani, Peter Schreiner, ''Quarta Crociata. Venezia - Bisanzio - Impero latino'', Venice, 2006, p.340\u201342</ref>), the [[Capetian House of Anjou|House of Anjou]] and the [[Tocco family]].<ref name=\"Haberstumpf2005\">[[#refHaberstumpf2005|Haberstumpf]], p.&nbsp;57\u201370.</ref> The rule of the family of Tocco lasted for 122 years, up until 1479, when Ottomans captured Cephalonia, Zante, Lefkada and Ithaca.<ref name=\"Haberstumpf2005\"/>\n\n=== The Venetian conquest ===\nOn 13 February 1386 Corfu became once more a Venetian possession and this time Venetian rule would last until the end of the Republic.<ref name=D95>[[#refDurrell1967|Durrell]], p.&nbsp;95.</ref> This was accomplished voluntary by the people of Corfu.<ref>[[#refDurrell1967|Durrell]], p.&nbsp;160.</ref> On 10 May, the Corfiotes appointed five ambassadors to submit to the Venetian senate.<ref name=D95/> The Ottomans made several attempts to capture Corfu, the first of which was in 1537.<ref>[[#refBlack2002|Black]], p.&nbsp;56.</ref> This attack led Venice to an alliance with the Pope and Emperor [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]], known as the [[Holy League (1538)|Holy League]], against the Ottoman Empire.<ref>[[#refIsom-Verhaaren1967|Isom-Verhaaren]], p.&nbsp;40.</ref> Another major unsuccessful Ottoman attack was [[Siege of Corfu (1716)|that of July 1716]].<ref>[[#refOttomanEmpire1976|A History of the Ottoman Empire to 1730]], p.&nbsp;210.</ref>\n[[File:Ionian Sea. Venetian possessions.jpg|thumb|left|Venetian possessions in the Ionian Sea area]]\nAfter the partition of the Byzantine Empire in 1204, Cythera fell into Venetian hands in 1238 through the marriage of [[Marco Venier, Marquess of Cerigo|Marco Venier]] with the daughter of the Greek lord of the island.<ref>Michael Angold, ''The Latin empire of Constantinople, 1204\u20131261: marriage strategies'' in ''Identities and Allegiances in the Eastern Mediterranean After 1204'' p 60</ref> Cythera and Anticythera constituted part of the ''{{lang|vec|[[Stato da M\u00e0r]]}}'' for the first time in 1363 followed by an interruption of a three-year Turkish rule, [[Ottoman\u2013Venetian War (1714\u20131718)|between 1715 and 1718]].<ref>[[#refMaltezou1980|Maltezou]], p.&nbsp;33.</ref> With the [[Treaty of Passarowitz]] Cythera and Anticythera passed to the Venetian Republic and remained under its control until its fall, in 1797.<ref>[[#refMiller1908|Miller]], p.&nbsp;633\u2013638.</ref>\n\nThe Turkish rule in the three islands of Cephalonia, Zante and Ithaca was short-lived. In 1481, two years after the beginning of the Turkish rule, Antonio Tocco invaded and briefly occupied Cephalonia and Zante but he was soon driven out by the Venetians.<ref>[[#refBabinger1992|Babinger]], p.&nbsp;384.</ref> Zante was officially recovered by the Venetians in 1485.<ref>[[#refWard1912|Ward]], p.&nbsp;26.</ref><ref name=\"Minoglou2005\">[[#refMcCabeHarlaftisMinoglou2005|McCabe, Harlaftis & Minoglou]], p.&nbsp;98.</ref><ref name=\"Setton1978\">[[#refSetton1978|Setton]], p.&nbsp;515.</ref> Then, Cephalonia, after sixteen years of Turkish occupation (1484\u20131500), became part of the ''{{lang|vec|Stato da M\u00e0r}}'' on 24 December 1500, with the [[Siege of the Castle of St. George]].<ref name=\"Minoglou2005\"/><ref name=\"Setton1978\"/> Finally, Ithaca, following the fate of Cephalonia, was conquered by Venice in 1503.<ref>[[#refScammell2011|Scammell]], p.&nbsp;119.</ref>\n\nLefkada, part of the [[Despotate of Epirus]] since the latter's foundation in 1205, was incorporated by [[Leonardo I Tocco]] into the County of Cephalonia in 1362.<ref>[[#refHeurtley1967|Heurtley]], p.&nbsp;57.</ref> The Despotate of Epirus was one of the three Byzantine Empires in exile created after the Fourth Crusade in 1204.<ref>[[#refNicol2010|Nicol]], p.&nbsp;4.</ref> Following the fate of the other central Ionian Islands, it was captured by the Turks in 1479 and then by the Venetians in 1502.<ref name=\"Haberstumpf2005\"/><ref>[[#refDeRoo1924|De Roo]], p.&nbsp;56.</ref> However, Venetian rule did not last, as Lefkada was given back to the Ottoman Empire one year later.<ref>[[#refMiller1908|Miller]], p.&nbsp;570\u2013571.</ref> Turkish rule over Lefkada lasted for over 200 years, from 1479 to 1684, when [[Francesco Morosini]] attacked and subdued the island during the [[Morean War]].<ref>[[#refHeurtley1967|Heurtley]], p.&nbsp;65.</ref> Lefkada, however, did not become officially Venetian until 1718, with the signature of the Treaty of Passarowitz.<ref>[[#refForeignOffice1850|Foreign Office of Great Britain]], p.&nbsp;353.</ref>\n\n=== Dissolution of the Republic and aftermath ===\n{{details|Fall of the Republic of Venice}}\n[[File:Italian States in 1789.png|thumb|397x397px|Political map of Italy in the year 1789, showing the Ionian islands of the Republic of Venice in detail]]\n\n[[Napoleon Bonaparte]] declared war against Venice on 3 May 1797.<ref>[[#refAlison1835|Alison]], p.&nbsp;283.</ref> The signing of the [[Treaty of Campo Formio]], on 17 October 1797, marked the dissolution of the Republic of Venice and the sharing of its territories between France and Austria.<ref>[[#refJervis-White-Jervis1852|Jervis-White-Jervis]], p.&nbsp;159.</ref> The lands of the ''{{lang|vec|Terraferma}}'' up to the River [[Adige]], the city itself and the possessions of the [[Balkan Peninsula|Balkan peninsula]] of [[Istria]] and [[Dalmatia]] were yielded to Austria.<ref>[[#refSchroeder1996|Schroeder]], p.&nbsp;171.</ref> The Ionian Islands, part of Venetian maritime territories, were ceded to France.<ref>[[#refAlison1835|Alison]], p.&nbsp;308.</ref> Napoleon organized the islands into three [[French departments of Greece|departments]]: {{lang|fr|[[Corcyre]]}}, {{lang|fr|[[Ithaque]]}}, and {{lang|fr|[[Mer-\u00c9g\u00e9e]]}}.<ref>[[#refRodger1964|Rodger]], p.&nbsp;88.</ref><ref name=\"R1\">[[#refRulhi\u00e8re1800|Rulhi\u00e8re]], p.&nbsp;1.</ref> The first included the islands of Corfu and Paxos, as well as the former Venetian settlements of [[Butrint]] and [[Parga]] situated in [[Epirus]].<ref name=\"R1\"/> The second department was formed by the islands of Cephalonia, Ithaca and Lefkada and the cities of Preveza and Vonitsa, whereas Zante and Cerigo were part of the third department.<ref>[[#refRulhi\u00e8re1800|Rulhi\u00e8re]], p.&nbsp;2.</ref> The French rule, however, did not last as [[Russian Empire|Russia]] allied with the Ottoman Empire in September 1798 and in 1799 a Russo-Ottoman naval expedition [[Siege of Corfu (1798\u20131799)|captured the islands]].<ref>[[#refSchroeder1996|Schroeder]], p.&nbsp;182.</ref> With the signing of a treaty between Russia and the [[Ottoman Porte|Porte]] on 21 March 1800, an independent island republic under the protection of both the empires was established.<ref>[[#refPratt1978|Pratt]], p.&nbsp;81.</ref> The name of the new state was agreed to be the ''\"[[Septinsular Republic]]\"'' and included all the territories of the three former French departments except for the continental possessions of Parga, [[Preveza]], [[Vonitsa]] and Butrint.<ref name=QR118>[[#refQR1820|The Quarterly review]], p.&nbsp;118.</ref> With the [[Treaty of Tilsit]] in 1807, the seven islands were given back to France by Russia.<ref>[[#refXenos1865|Xenos]], p.&nbsp;224.</ref> In October 1809, Great Britain took possession of all the islands with the exception of Corfu and Paxos, which was only surrendered in 1814.<ref>[[#refFleming1999|Fleming]], p.&nbsp;114.</ref><ref>[[#refRoberts1861|Roberts]], p.&nbsp;306.</ref> In 1815, the Ionian Islands became a British protectorate under the name [[United States of the Ionian Islands]].<ref name=QR118/>\n\n== Administration ==\nThe civil and military governor of the Ionian Islands was the ''[[Provveditore generale da Mar]]'', who lived on Corfu and had the supreme peacetime command of the [[Venetian navy]].{{sfn|Da Mosto|1940|p=19}}{{sfn|Arbel|2013|p=152}} In wartime, due to his absence at the head of the fleet, he was sometimes replaced by a ''Provveditore generale delle Tre Isole'' (\"Superintendent general of the Three Islands\"), referring to Corfu, Zante, and Cephalonia. As a result of the two prolonged wars of the 17th century\u2014the [[War of Candia]] (1645\u20131669) and the [[Morean War]] (1684\u20131699)\u2014the office acquired a more permanent nature, and was renamed to ''Provveditore generale delle Quattro Isole'' after the [[Siege of Santa Maura|capture of Santa Maura]] in 1684.{{sfn|Da Mosto|1940|p=19}}{{sfn|Arbel|2013|p=152}}\n \n[[File:Corfu Pinargenti 1573.jpg|thumb|180px|left|The [[Old Fortress]] of Corfu in 1573]]\nAuthorities in the islands were divided into two types: the Venetian ones, occupied by Venetians and represented the sovereign state and its political and military power over the Islands, and the domestic authorities, which were appointed by the Communal Council (''{{lang|it|Consiglio della Comunit\u00e0}}'').<ref>[[#refMiller1908|Miller]], p.&nbsp;604.</ref> The Venetians were appointed by the [[Great Council of Venice]]. There were three officials constituting the ''{{lang|it|reggimento}}'' (\"regime\") of each island.<ref>[[#refDudan1938|Dudan]], p.&nbsp;166.</ref> The head of the ''{{lang|it|reggimento}}'' had the title of ''{{lang|it|[[provveditore]]}}'' in all the islands except for Corfu, where he was called ''{{lang|it|[[bailo of Corfu|bailo]]}}''.<ref>[[#refLunzi1858|Lunzi]], p.&nbsp;251.</ref> The title could only be held by a nobleman.<ref name=zorzi136>[[#refZorzi1983|Zorzi]], p.&nbsp;136.</ref> The subordinate Venetian officials were the ''{{lang|it|[[consigliere|consiglieri]]}}'', two on each island, who performed administrative and judicial functions along with the ''{{lang|it|provveditore}}'' of each island.<ref>[[#refSaint-Sauveur1800|Saint-Sauveur]], p.&nbsp;56\u201363.</ref> The ''{{lang|it|provveditore}}''{{'}}s responsibilities also included security from hostile raids, taxation, religious and other issues.<ref>[[#refLunzi1858|Lunzi]], p.&nbsp;102, 150.</ref>\n\nIn Corfu the Venetian officials included a ''{{lang|it|bailo}}'', a ''{{lang|it|provveditore}}'' and a ''{{lang|it|capitano}}'', two ''{{lang|it|consiglieri}}'', a ''{{lang|it|capitano della cittadella}}'' and a ''{{lang|it|castellano della fortezza}}''. In Cephalonia and Zante there were only one ''{{lang|it|provveditore}}'' and two ''{{lang|it|consiglieri}}''.{{sfn|Da Mosto|1940|pp=19\u201320}} When Lefkada (Santa Maura) was incorporated a ''{{lang|it|Provveditore}}'' was appointed, while the archives also record the occasional appointment of a ''{{lang|it|Provveditore straordinario}}'',{{sfn|Da Mosto|1940|p=20}} although, in 1595, another ''{{lang|it|provveditore}}'' was appointed to the Fortress of Asso.<ref name=FMS46>[[#refFr\u00e9chetMeghraouiStucchi2008|Fr\u00e9chet, Meghraoui & Stucchi]], p.&nbsp;46.</ref> In Cythera the ''{{lang|it|reggimento}}'' included both a ''{{lang|it|provveditore}}'' and a ''{{lang|it|castellano}}''.{{sfn|Da Mosto|1940|p=21}} In imitation of the metropolis, the domestic authorities comprised both a ''{{lang|it|Consiglio Maggiore}}'' and a ''{{lang|it|Consiglio Minore}}'' composed of members of the local aristocracy.<ref name=zorzi136/>\n\nThere were ten fortresses throughout the islands, with one on each island serving as its capital.<ref name=FMS46/> On Corfu, however, there were three fortresses; two in the town of Corfu and the [[Angelokastro (Corfu)|Angelokastro]].<ref name=FMS46/> On Cephalonia there were two, the castle of St. George or the Fortress of Cephalonia (''{{lang|it|Citt\u00e0 di Cefalonia}}'') and the Fortress of [[Assos, Kefalonia|Asso]] (''{{lang|it|Fortezza d'Asso}}'') in the northern part.<ref name=FMS46/><ref>[http://romeartlover.tripod.com/Cefalonia.html Fortress of Cefalonia]</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Corfcefzan.jpg|thumb|right|120px|Two ''{{lang|it|solidi}}'' coin]]\nThe Ionian economy during the Venetian period was largely based on exporting local products.<ref>[[#refMcCabeHarlaftisMinoglou2005|McCabe, Harlaftis & Minoglou]], p.&nbsp;101.</ref> The most important of the agricultural products of Corfu was [[olive oil]].<ref>[[#refThiriet1975|Thiriet]], p.&nbsp;174\u2013189.</ref> On the islands of Cephalonia and Zante the main exports were [[raisins]], olive oil and [[wine]].<ref>[[#refPartsch1890|Partsch]], p.&nbsp;97\u201398.</ref><ref>[[#refRulhi\u00e8re1800|Rulhi\u00e8re]], p.&nbsp;5.</ref> One of the most significant exports was  olive oil. Groves of [[olive trees]] were planted throughout the islands during the Venetian period as olive oil was important to Venice's economy.<ref name=\"Portfolio112\">[[#refPortfolio1836|The Portfolio]], p.&nbsp;112.</ref> Although the production of it was successful, the Republic only allowed exportation to Venice.<ref name=\"Portfolio112\"/> Statistics for the years 1766\u201370 indicate 1,905,917 olive trees on Corfu, 113,161 on Zante, 38,516 on Cephalonia, 44,146 on Lefkada and 31,884 on Cythera.<ref>[[#refMiller1908|Miller]], p.&nbsp;614.</ref>\n\nNevertheless, raisin exports were the most important export of the islands during the Venetian rule. By the early 18th century Zante, Cephalonia, and part of Ithaca had become a major centre of the currant trade.<ref>[[#refChristensen2000|Christensen]], p.&nbsp;40.</ref> Because of the fierce competition in the raisin trade between Venice and the United Kingdom, Venice prohibited the free export of raisins from the islands.<ref>[[#refFusaro1996|Fusaro]], p.&nbsp;161-168.</ref> Another measure was the ''{{lang|it|nuova imposta}}'', a heavy export tax for foreign ships.<ref>[[#refOrtalli1998|Ortalli]], p.&nbsp;205.</ref>\n\nThe currency of the islands during Venetian rule was the [[Venetian lira]], as in Venice.<ref>[[#refLampros1968|Lampros]], p.&nbsp;11.</ref> There was a special issue for the Islands; the observe side of it has the complete or shortened inscription CORFU/CEFALONIA/ZANTE in three lines. The reserve depicts the winged and haloed lion of Saint Marc in a front view, holding the book of the Gospel in his fore-paws.<ref>[[#refLampros1968|Lampros]], p.&nbsp;12.</ref> The Ionian Islands formed part of the [[Trade route#Maritime republics' Mediterranean trade|Venetian maritime trade route]] to the Orient.<ref>[[#refClayton2005|Clayton]], p.&nbsp;19.</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nWhen the central Ionian Islands were captured by Venice their population was very low and Ithaca was completely uninhabited.<ref>[[#refSathas1972|Sathas]], p.&nbsp;155.</ref> To address this problem, a small colonisation to the islands took place. [[Catholicism|Catholic]] [[Italians]] from ''{{lang|vec|[[Terraferma]]}}'' (later called [[Corfiot Italians]]<ref>[https://6612springbottomway.blogspot.com/2018/12/blog-post.html History of the Corfiot Italians]</ref> and [[Orthodoxy|Orthodox]] [[Greeks]] from the ''{{lang|vec|Stato da M\u00e0r}}'' were transferred to the islands as part of the colonisation.<ref>[[#refKonomos1968|Konomos]], p.&nbsp;9</ref>.\u03a4he population eventually increased: in 1765\u201366 it had reached 111,439; in 1780, the population was 150,908.<ref name=\"Kosmatou611\">[[#refKosmatou2000|Kosmatou]], p.&nbsp;611.</ref> Fourteen years later, there were 155,770 inhabitants throughout the islands.<ref name=\"Kosmatou611\"/>\n\nThese are some figures concerning the population of each island during the Venetian period:<ref>[[#refPaparrigopoulos1860|Paparrigopoulos]], p.&nbsp;213.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"sortable\" border=\"1px\" cellpadding=\"4px\" cellspacing=\"0px\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; border: 1px solid #CCC;\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n! Island\n! 1470\n! 1500\n! 1528\n! 1532\n! 1568\n! 1583\n! 1675\n! 1684\n! 1760\n! 1766\n|-\n| [[Kerkyra|Corfu]] ||  ||  ||  || 14,246 ||  || 19,221 || 20,000 ||  ||  || 44,333\n|-\n| [[Paxos]] ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || 4,150 ||  \n|-\n| [[Lefkada]] ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || 9,000 || 12,000 || 11,760\n|-\n| [[Ithaca]] ||  ||  ||  ||  || 300 ||  ||  ||  || 2,500 ||  \n|-\n| [[Cephalonia]] ||  || 14,000 ||  ||  ||  || 25,543 ||  ||  ||  || 21,659\n|-\n| [[Zante]] ||  ||  || 17,255 ||  ||  || 14,054 || 25,000 ||  ||  || 25,325\n|-\n| [[Kythira|Cythera]] || 500 ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || 6,000 || 6,183\n|}\n\n=== Language and education ===\nDuring the Venetian period all public acts were drawn up in the [[Venetian language]],<ref>[[#refBrewster1832|Brewster]], p.&nbsp;396.</ref> the official language of the Government.<ref>[[#refFitzMaurice1864|FitzMaurice]], p.&nbsp;39.</ref> [[Greek language|Greek]] remained spoken by the peasantry whereas Venetian was adopted by the upper class and it was generally preferred within the towns (like in Corfu city were nearly all the population spoke the ''Veneto de Mar'').<ref>[[#refMiller1908|Miller]], p.&nbsp;613.</ref> Thus, the Venetian language became, if not the common language of the Ionians, at least the [[prestige language|prestigious language]].<ref>[[#refSaint-Sauveur1800|Saint-Sauveur]], p.&nbsp;189\u2013190.</ref> The Venetians did little in the area of education,<ref>[[#refLunzi1858|Lunzi]], p.&nbsp;496.</ref> mainly due to the fact that schooling was not considered a responsibility of the state at that time in Europe but a private matter.<ref>[[#refLane1973|Lane]], p.&nbsp;313.</ref> Some authors believe that this was done intentionally by Venice, as part of its colonial policy.<ref>[[#refDavy1842|Davy]], p.&nbsp;31. Chapter 1 ''Historical Notices on the Ionian Islands and Malta'' by John Davy: \"No people or government better understood the value of the old adage, that knowledge is power, than the Venetians; and the method they pursued to retain the Ionians in ignorance, was strictly in conformity with the rest of their policy\"</ref> People belonging to the upper classes were more likely to be educated and to have studied at an Italian university, usually the [[University of Padua]].<ref>[[#refLunzi1858|Lunzi]], p.&nbsp;248.</ref><ref>[[#refAugliera1996|Augliera]], p.&nbsp;83\u201384.</ref> Modelled after the academies operating at that time in Venice, the first literary academy, ''{{lang|it|Accademia degli Assicurati}}'', was founded in Corfu in 1656 by individuals.<ref name=Lunzi448>[[#refLunzi1858|Lunzi]], p.&nbsp;448.</ref> It had as an emblem two rocks beneath a winged lion, with an inscription ''{{lang|la|His Semper}}'' hovering in the air.<ref name=Lunzi448/>\n\n=== Religion ===\n[[File:Katholikos Kathedrikos Naos ton Agion Christoforou kai Iakovou - Corfu (16 July 2010).jpg|thumb|right|150px|The Catholic Cathedral of Corfu]]\nVenetians, being Catholics, retained the privileges enjoyed by the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Corfu, Zakynthos and Cephalonia|Latin bishopric]] of the islands under the Count Palatine dynasties.<ref name=\"Miller208\">[[#refMiller1921|Miller]], p.&nbsp;208.</ref> The Catholics were not numerous, and during the Venetian period, they were mainly concentrated in Corfu and Cephalonia.<ref name=\"Miller209\">[[#refMiller1921|Miller]], p.&nbsp;209.</ref> Most of them were descendants of Italian settlers but there were some conversions by Greeks to Catholicism.<ref name=\"Clogg26\">[[#refClogg2002|Clogg]], p.&nbsp;26.</ref> According to the law, Greek Orthodox priests and monks had to accept the Catholics as their superiors,<ref name=\"Clogg26\"/> though the Venetians placed the interests of the Republic ahead of those of the [[Papacy]].<ref name=\"Miller208\"/> [[Exogamy|Mixed marriages]] between Catholic and Orthodox Christians were allowed.<ref name=\"Miller209\"/> These two were the main factors in the decline of Roman Catholicism in the Islands.<ref name=\"Miller209\"/><ref>[[#refYoung1977|Young]], p.&nbsp;96.</ref>\n\n[[Jews]] were also a native religious group to the Islands during the Venetian period. They were even fewer in number than the Catholics; in 1797 the number of Jews in Corfu appears to have been only two thousand.<ref>[[#refFitzMaurice1864|FitzMaurice]], p.&nbsp;52.</ref> Jewish presence in Corfu can be traced since the times of the [[Principality of Taranto]].<ref>[[#refFitzMaurice1864|FitzMaurice]], p.&nbsp;47.</ref> In Cephalonia, there is evidence of Jewish habitation in the old capital, the Castle of St. George, since the early 17th century.<ref>[[#refChasiotes1997|Chasiotes]], p.&nbsp;97.</ref> When the capital of the island was transferred to [[Argostoli]] the Jews resettled there.<ref>[[#refFitzMaurice1864|FitzMaurice]], p.&nbsp;53.</ref>\n\n=== Social structure ===\nThe social structure of the islands followed that of Venice. The whole population was divided into three classes: the [[nobles]] (''{{lang|it|nobili}}''), the [[bourgeoisie]] (''{{lang|it|citadini}}'') and the [[common people]] (''{{lang|it|populari}}'').<ref>[[#refBiresKardamitse-Adame2004|Bires & Kardamitse-Adame]], p.&nbsp;32.</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n[[File:Emblem of Septinsular republic.svg|thumb|left|150px|The Emblem of the Septinsular Republic, based on the [[Flag of Veneto|Flag of Venice]]]]\nThroughout Venice's old possessions, but above all in the Ionian islands, the memory of the Republic is deeply rooted in the population, who recall it with a shade of nostalgia even after so much time and so many events.<ref>[[#refZorzi1983|Zorzi]], p.&nbsp;229. \"In the ancient Venetian kingdoms, above all in the Ionian islands, the memory of the Republic is deeply rooted in the population, who recall it with a shade of nostalgia even after so much time and so many events.\"</ref> Because of the long Venetian period, the manners and traditions of the inhabitants of the Ionian Islands are a mixture of Greek and Italian.<ref>[[#refVaudoncourtWalton1816|Vaudoncourt & Walton]], p.&nbsp;409.</ref> The Venetian influence is illustrated in all aspects of culture and everyday life. In 1800 the [[Septinsular Republic]] was established; its flag design was based on the flag of the Republic of Venice.<ref>[[#refSmyth1854|Smyth]], p.&nbsp;52.</ref> In addition, Italian was the co-official language of both the Septinsular Republic and the [[United States of the Ionian Islands]].<ref>{{lang|it|[[#refConst1849|Le tre costituzioni (1800, 1803, 1817) delle Sette Isole Jonie]]}}, p.&nbsp;191.</ref> Because of its status, Italian was also taught at schools along with Greek and English (Ionian Islands were a [[protectorate]] of the [[United Kingdom]] from 1815 until 1864).<ref name=journal83>[[#refjournal1831|The Quarterly journal of education]], p.&nbsp;83.</ref> In the First Year of the secondary education, for instance, Greek was taught four times a week, Italian three times and English twice.<ref name=journal83/> In the Greek Census of 1907, 4,675 people from the Ionian Islands stated [[Catholicism]] as their denomination, about 1.8% of the total population (254,494), while 2,541 (1%) Ionians stated Italian as their mother tongue, making it the second language by number of speakers.<ref>[http://dlib.statistics.gr/Book/GRESYE_02_0101_00015.pdf 1907 Census of the Kingdom of Greece 387 pages]</ref> The Italian language remains popular on the islands. The Hellenic Union of Eptanisians, a civil non-profit company working for the promotion of the Heptanesian Culture, objected to the decision of the Ministry to abolish the teaching of Italian in schools, saying that \"especially for the Ionian Islands the selection of the Italian language has become a tradition for their schools, but also a necessary language because of the many tourists from Italy and other relations e.g. cultural, commercial, etc., of the islands with the country\" and they propose \"respect for the choice of the children and recognition of their right to learn the language they want and especially the Italian as it's the language with the greatest preference on the Ionian Islands\".<ref>[http://enosiee.blogspot.com/2011/08/blog-post.html Press Release for the abolition of the Italian language] - Hellenic Union of Eptanisians, 1-8-2011</ref>\n\n[[File:Isole-jonie.jpg|thumb|right|140px|Italian stamp during the occupation overprinted with ''{{lang|it|Isole Jonie}}'']]\nThese cultural remnants of the Venetian period were the pretext of [[Benito Mussolini|Mussolini]]'s desire to incorporate the Ionian Islands into the [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Kingdom of Italy]].<ref>[[#refRodogno2006|Rodogno]], p.&nbsp;72.</ref><ref>[[#refRodogno2006|Rodogno]], p.&nbsp;84.</ref> Even before the outbreak of [[World War II]] and the [[Greek-Italian War]], Mussolini had expressed his wish to annex the Ionian Islands as part of his wider plans for an [[Italian Empire]] centered around the [[Mediterranean Sea]].<ref>[[#refKnox1986|Knox]], p.&nbsp;140.</ref> On 15 October, in a meeting in the [[Palazzo Venezia]], he made the final decision to invade Greece.<ref>[[#refHoyt1994|Hoyt]], p.&nbsp;190.</ref> His initial goal was the occupation of Corfu, Zante and Cephalonia.<ref>[[#refSchreiberStegemannVogel1995|Schreiber, Stegemann & Voge]], p.&nbsp;410.</ref> After the fall of Greece, in early April 1941, the invaders divided its lands into three occupation zones; the Italians occupied much of the country, including the Ionians.<ref>[[#refWeverGoethemWouters2006|Wever, Goethem & Wouters]], p.&nbsp;250.</ref> Mussolini informed General [[Carlo Geloso]] that the Ionian Islands would form a separate [[Italian province]] through a ''{{lang|la|de facto}}'' annexation, but the Germans would not approve it.<ref name=\"Rodogno85\">[[#refRodogno2006|Rodogno]], p.&nbsp;85.</ref> The Italian authorities nevertheless continued to prepare the ground for the annexation.<ref name=\"Rodogno85\"/> Finally, on 22 April 1941, after discussions between the German and Italian rulers, German ''{{lang|de|F\u00fchrer}}'' [[Adolf Hitler]] agreed that Italy could proceed with a ''{{lang|la|de facto}}'' annexation of the islands.<ref>[[#refCorvajaMiller2008|Corvaja & Miller]], p.&nbsp;170.</ref><ref>[[#refRodogno2006|Rodogno]], p.&nbsp;104.</ref>  From then on, until the end of the war, the islands passed through a phase of [[Italianization]] in all areas, from their administration to their economy.<ref>[[#refRodogno2006|Rodogno]], p.&nbsp;258.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|History|Greece|Middle Ages}}\n* [[Corfiot Italians]]\n* [[History of the Republic of Venice]]\n* [[Timeline of the Republic of Venice]]\n* [[Coinage of the Republic of Venice]]\n* [[Ottoman wars in Europe]]\n* [[Ionian School (music)|Ionian School of music]]\n* [[Heptanese School (literature)|Ionian School of literature]]\n* [[Heptanese School (painting)|Ionian School of painting]]\n* [[Corfiot Italians]]\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Footnotes ===\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* {{Cite book| first=| last=| title=A History of the Ottoman Empire to 1730| publisher=Cambridge University Press| year=1976| isbn=| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nUs7AAAAIAAJ&dq| ref=refOttomanEmpire1976| accessdate=3 September 2011}}\n* {{Cite book| first=Archibald| last=Alison| title=History of Europe from the commencement of the French Revolution in MDCCLXXXIX to the Restoration of the Bourbons in MDCCCXV, Volume III| publisher=Blackwood| year=1835| isbn=| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hq5BAAAAcAAJ&dq| ref=refAlison1835| accessdate=2 September 2011}}\n* {{cite book | title=A Companion to Venetian History, 1400&ndash;1797 | first=Benjamin | last=Arbel | chapter = Venice's Maritime Empire in the Early Modern Period | pages = 125\u2013253 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=2ascAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA125 |year=2013 |publisher=BRILL |isbn=978-90-04-25252-3 | ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book| first=Letterio| last=Augliera| title=Libri, politica, religione nel Levante del Seicento| publisher=Istituto veneto di scienze, lettere ed arti| year=1996| isbn=88-86166-29-X| url=https://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN888616629X| language=Italian| ref=refAugliera1996| accessdate=10 August 2011}}\n* {{Cite book| first=| last=Archivio di Stato di Venezia| title=L'Archivio di stato di Venezia: indice generale, storico, descrittivo ed analitico| publishe