{"title_page": "Sam McCready (actor)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Sam McCready.jpg|thumb|Sam McCready at Lyric Theatre, Belfast, 2017|300px]]\n'''Sam McCready''' (22 November 1936<ref name=\"Campbell\">{{cite news | url=http://www.irishnews.com/arts/2016/04/23/news/actor-and-director-sam-mccready-brings-percy-french-to-life-in-melodies-of-unforgotten-years-494919/ | title=Actor and director Sam McCready brings Percy French to life in Melodies of Unforgotten Years | work=[[The Irish News]] | date=23 April 2016 | accessdate=21 May 2016 | author=Campbell, Brian}}</ref> \u2013 10 February 2019)<ref name=\"Gamble\">{{cite news | url=https://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/ni-born-actor-and-playwright-sam-mccready-dies-1-8805746 | title=NI-born actor and playwright Sam McCready dies | work=[[The News Letter]] | date=11 February 2019 | accessdate=11 February 2019 | author = Gamble, Stephen}}</ref> was an actor, [[theatre director]] and playwright who was born in [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"Lagan\">{{cite web | url=http://laganpress.co/authors/sam-mccready | title=Sam McCready | publisher=Lagan Press | work=Authors | accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref> One of 13 children of David and Sarah McCready, he lived in Northern Ireland and in the United States with his wife Joan Carslake whom he met in 1958 at Stranmillis College, Belfast, and married in 1962.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news | url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/life/features/my-people-sam-mccready-on-his-special-relationships-31416350.html | title=My people: Sam McCready on his special relationships | work=[[The Belfast Telegraph]] | date=31 July 2015 | accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref> They had two children.\n\nSam was a founder member of the [[Lyric Theatre, Belfast]], with whom he founded the Lyric Youth Theatre (1968), and later still the Lyric Drama Studio (1978).  He performed and directed theatre productions in Europe and the US, and with Joan McCready was the founder and co-Artistic Director of Two-for-One Productions, a touring company which specializes in small-scale productions. He conducted the Drama Workshop at the Yeats International Summer School, Sligo regularly from 1999. \n\nHe also gained a reputation as a painter with major exhibitions in Ireland and the US. Represented by ArtisAnn Gallery, Bloomfield Avenue, Belfast.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nBorn in East Belfast, he moved to [[Hillsborough, County Down]], when the family home at 6 Tower Street was destroyed in the [[Belfast Blitz]].  There he attended St. John's Primary School, Hillsborough, and returned to Belfast in 1945, living with his parents at 144 Connsbrook Avenue.  He attended Strand Primary School (1945\u201348), and Grosvenor High School (1948\u20131954), and after completing his Senior Certificate, he accepted a post as Permanent Clerk, Northern Ireland Civil Service, Family Allowances Branch (1954\u20131956).  \n\nHe returned to full-time education in 1956 beginning his teacher training at [[Stranmillis University College]], graduating with a Cert. Ed (with Special Merit), 1960.<ref>''Baptism by Fire'', Lagan Press, 2007</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\n\nHis first teaching appointment was at Fane Street School, an unreorganized Primary School in Belfast, where he taught Art (1960\u201362). He was appointed Advertising Manager at Berkshire Hosiery, Newtownards in 1962 but returned to full-time teaching as Head of Drama at Orangefield Boys' Secondary School in 1964, followed by his appointment as Head of English.\n\nIn 1969, he accepted a post in the Drama Department at University College of North Wales, where he completed his MA (1969\u20131978). and was appointed Head of Drama, Stranmillis Training College (1978\u20131982).  An invitation to direct in New York brought him to the US, where he was appointed Professor of Theatre, University of Maryland, Baltimore, County, a position he held with distinction until his retirement from full-time teaching in 2001.  From then on he maintained, with his wife Joan McCready, a successful theatre career as actor, playwright and director.\n\n==Professional training==\n\nMcCready was trained at the Guildhall School of Music and Drama (LGSM) and the [[London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art]] (LLCM).\n\nThe plays he directed include ''A Time to Speak'', a dramatisation of the [[Holocaust]] memoir by [[Helen Lewis (choreographer)|Helen Lewis]], which was performed at the [[Lyric Theatre, Belfast]].<ref name=\"Lagan\"/>\n\n==Death==\n\nSam McCready died in the [[United States]] on 10 February 2019, aged 82.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishnews.com/news/northernirelandnews/2019/02/12/news/tributes-paid-to-actor-and-playwright-sam-mccready-1549755/ |title=Tributes paid to actor and playwright Sam McCready |work=The Irish News | author=Mcgonagle, Suzanne |date=12 February 2019|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/sam-mccready-doyen-of-ulster-theatre-dies-at-the-age-of-82-in-united-states-37806364.html |title=Sam McCready, doyen of Ulster theatre, dies at the age of 82 in United States |work=Belfast Telegraph | author=Laurence White |date=12 February 2019|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Plays and publications==\n* ''Lucille Lortel: The Queen of Off-Broadway'' (1993)\n* ''A William Butler Yeats Encyclopedia'' (1997)\n* ''Coole Lady: The Extraordinary Story of Lady Gregory'' (2005)\n* ''Baptism by Fire: My Life with Mary O\u2019Malley and the Lyric Players'' (2008)\n* ''The Great Yeats!'' : ''Remarkable Father of a Remarkable Family'' (2010)\n*''A Time to Speak'': adapted from the Holocaust memoir by [[Helen Lewis (choreographer)|Helen Lewis]] (2011)\n*''Dickens at the Ulster Hall'' (2012)\n*''Percy French: Melodies of Unforgotten Years'' (2014)\n*''No Surrender'': adapted from the memoir of a Belfast childhood by Robert Harbinson (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.culturenorthernireland.org/article/2064/sam-mccready#sthash.s2D8bo31.dpuf \"Censorship, theatre and cash: Sam McCready discovers that true success is a state of mind\"], [[Culture Northern Ireland]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCready, Sam}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Stranmillis University College]]\n[[Category:Irish theatre directors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Belfast]]\n[[Category:Male writers from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Schoolteachers from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Writers from Belfast]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Sam McCready.jpg|thumb|Sam McCready at Lyric Theatre, Belfast, 2017|300px]]\n'''Sam McCready''' (22 November 1936<ref name=\"Campbell\">{{cite news | url=http://www.irishnews.com/arts/2016/04/23/news/actor-and-director-sam-mccready-brings-percy-french-to-life-in-melodies-of-unforgotten-years-494919/ | title=Actor and director Sam McCready brings Percy French to life in Melodies of Unforgotten Years | work=[[The Irish News]] | date=23 April 2016 | accessdate=21 May 2016 | author=Campbell, Brian}}</ref> \u2013 10 February 2019)<ref name=\"Gamble\">{{cite news | url=https://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/ni-born-actor-and-playwright-sam-mccready-dies-1-8805746 | title=NI-born actor and playwright Sam McCready dies | work=[[The News Letter]] | date=11 February 2019 | accessdate=11 February 2019 | author = Gamble, Stephen}}</ref> was an actor, [[theatre director]] and playwright who was born in [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"Lagan\">{{cite web | url=http://laganpress.co/authors/sam-mccready | title=Sam McCready | publisher=Lagan Press | work=Authors | accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref> One of 13 children of David and Sarah McCready, he lived in Northern Ireland and in the United States with his wife Joan Carslake whom he met in 1958 at Stranmillis College, Belfast, and married in 1962.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news | url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/life/features/my-people-sam-mccready-on-his-special-relationships-31416350.html | title=My people: Sam McCready on his special relationships | work=[[The Belfast Telegraph]] | date=31 July 2015 | accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref> They had two children.\n\nSam was a founder member of the [[Lyric Theatre, Belfast]], with whom he founded the Lyric Youth Theatre (1968), and later still the Lyric Drama Studio (1978).  He performed and directed theatre productions in Europe and the US, and with Joan McCready was the founder and co-Artistic Director of Two-for-One Productions, a touring company which specializes in small-scale productions. He conducted the Drama Workshop at the Yeats International Summer School, Sligo regularly from 1999. \n\nHe also gained a reputation as a painter with major exhibitions in Ireland and the US. Represented by ArtisAnn Gallery, Bloomfield Avenue, Belfast.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nBorn in East Belfast, he moved to [[Hillsborough, County Down]], when the family home at 6 Tower Street was destroyed in the [[Belfast Blitz]].  There he attended St. John's Primary School, Hillsborough, and returned to Belfast in 1945, living with his parents at 144 Connsbrook Avenue.  He attended Strand Primary School (1945\u201348), and Grosvenor High School (1948\u20131954), and after completing his Senior Certificate, he accepted a post as Permanent Clerk, Northern Ireland Civil Service, Family Allowances Branch (1954\u20131956).  \n\nHe returned to full-time education in 1956 beginning his teacher training at [[Stranmillis University College]], graduating with a Cert. Ed (with Special Merit), 1960.<ref>''Baptism by Fire'', Lagan Press, 2007</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\n\nHis first teaching appointment was at Fane Street School, an unreorganized Primary School in Belfast, where he taught Art (1960\u201362). He was appointed Advertising Manager at Berkshire Hosiery, Newtownards in 1962 but returned to full-time teaching as Head of Drama at Orangefield Boys' Secondary School in 1964, followed by his appointment as Head of English.\n\nIn 1969, he accepted a post in the Drama Department at University College of North Wales, where he completed his MA (1969\u20131978). and was appointed Head of Drama, Stranmillis Training College (1978\u20131982).  An invitation to direct in New York brought him to the US, where he was appointed Professor of Theatre, University of Maryland, Baltimore, County, a position he held with distinction until his retirement from full-time teaching in 2001.  From then on he maintained, with his wife Joan McCready, a successful theatre career as actor, playwright and director.\n\n==Professional training==\n\nMcCready was trained at theGuildhall School of Music and Drama (LGSM) and the [[London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art]] (LLCM).\n\nThe plays he directed include ''A Time to Speak'', a dramatisation of the [[Holocaust]] memoir by [[Helen Lewis (choreographer)|Helen Lewis]], which was performed at the [[Lyric Theatre, Belfast]].<ref name=\"Lagan\"/>\n\n==Death==\n\nSam McCready died in the [[United States]] on 10 February 2019, aged 82.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishnews.com/news/northernirelandnews/2019/02/12/news/tributes-paid-to-actor-and-playwright-sam-mccready-1549755/ |title=Tributes paid to actor and playwright Sam McCready |work=The Irish News | author=Mcgonagle, Suzanne |date=12 February 2019|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/sam-mccready-doyen-of-ulster-theatre-dies-at-the-age-of-82-in-united-states-37806364.html |title=Sam McCready, doyen of Ulster theatre, dies at the age of 82 in United States |work=Belfast Telegraph | author=Laurence White |date=12 February 2019|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Plays and publications==\n* ''Lucille Lortel: The Queen of Off-Broadway'' (1993)\n* ''A William Butler Yeats Encyclopedia'' (1997)\n* ''Coole Lady: The Extraordinary Story of Lady Gregory'' (2005)\n* ''Baptism by Fire: My Life with Mary O\u2019Malley and the Lyric Players'' (2008)\n* ''The Great Yeats!'' : ''Remarkable Father of a Remarkable Family'' (2010)\n*''A Time to Speak'': adapted from the Holocaust memoir by [[Helen Lewis (choreographer)|Helen Lewis]] (2011)\n*''Dickens at the Ulster Hall'' (2012)\n*''Percy French: Melodies of Unforgotten Years'' (2014)\n*''No Surrender'': adapted from the memoir of a Belfast childhood by Robert Harbinson (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.culturenorthernireland.org/article/2064/sam-mccready#sthash.s2D8bo31.dpuf \"Censorship, theatre and cash: Sam McCready discovers that true success is a state of mind\"], [[Culture Northern Ireland]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCready, Sam}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Stranmillis University College]]\n[[Category:Irish theatre directors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Belfast]]\n[[Category:Male writers from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Schoolteachers from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Writers from Belfast]]\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProfessional training:Spacing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sam_McCready_(actor)"}
{"title_page": "Permude", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|for=Grammar, sentence structure, readability|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Permude\n| official_name                   = Permude\n| other_name                      = \n| nickname                        = \n| settlement_type                 = [[Gram panchayat]]\n| image_skyline                   = \n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Karnataka#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location of Permude in Karnataka, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|13.0015|N|74.8835|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Karnataka]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Dakshina Kannada]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[Tehsil]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Mangalore taluk|Mangalore taluk]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| leader_title1                   =\n| leader_name1                    = \n| leader_title2                   =\n| leader_name2                    = \n| unit_pref                       =  \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_total                = \n| population_metro                = \n| population_as_of                = \n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = \n| population_demonym              = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = \n| demographics1_title1            = \n| demographics1_info1             = \n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|Pincode(s)]]\n| postal_code                     = 574509.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pincode.net.in/KARNATAKA/DAKSHINA_KANNADA/P/PERMUDE|title=Postal Pincode|last=Postal|first=pincode -Permude|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n| area_code_type                  = \n| area_code                       = \n| registration_plate              = \n| blank2_name                     = \n| blank2_info                     = \n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n'''Permude''' is a village panchayat located in [[Mangalore taluk]] of [[Dakshina Kannada]] district in [[Karnataka]], [[India]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Quarterly Journal of the All-India Institute of Local Self-Government, Bombay (Volume 66) |date=1995 |publisher=The Institute |page=201 |url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=es&id=VjC2AAAAIAAJ&dq=permude+karnataka&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Permude+Mangalore+Taluka |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Kurukshetra, Volume 43, Issues 3-12|publisher=United Trade PressM|year=1984|isbn=|location=|pages=Page 114,115 &116}}</ref>Permude is derived from Perda Mudde ([[Tulu Language]]) as production of milk was plenty during early time.<ref>{{cite news |title=St John the Baptist Church, Permude to celebrate golden jubilee on Jan 13 |url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=375844 |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=[[Daijiworld Media]] |date=10 January 2016}}</ref> [[Bangalore]] is the state capital and it is located around 290.9 kilometers away from Permude.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Strengthening village democracy: proceedings of National Conference on Gram Sabha|first=|title=National institute of Rual Development, 2002|publisher=National Institute of Rural Development.|year=1999|isbn=|location=|pages=213,220}}</ref> The nearby villages surrounding Permude are [[Bajpe]] and [[Kinnigoli]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Quarterly Journal of the Local Self-Government Institute (Bombay)|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=aJmOAAAAMAAJ&q=permude&dq=permude&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjA68GA3NXoAhV2D2MBHY-4BUM4ChDoAQhVMAU|journal=Quarterly Journal of the Local Self-Government Institute (Bombay)|volume=|pages=201|via=The Institute, 1995 - Municipal government}}</ref> According to Census 2011 information, the location code or village code of Permude village is 617478. The total geographical area of village is 742.43 hectares.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Special Economic Zones in India: A Study with Special Reference to Polepally|first=|title=Special Economic Zones in India:|publisher=Daanish Books|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=32}}</ref> Permude also comes under [[Mangalore Special Economic Zone]] or MSEZ.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://csez.com/rti/php/sezunit_details.php?zonecode=6&pg=u|title=List of Industries and Villages under|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Daijiworld News Portal|first=|url=https://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=109246|title=Permude GP Serves Notice to MSEZ over Illegal Construction|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Mangalore SEZ|url=http://www.itpi.org.in/uploads/journalfiles/jan4_10.pdf|journal=Towards Greater Economic|volume=India Journal 7 - 1|pages=55|via=Institute of Town Planners, India Journal 7 - 1}}</ref> Kudubis is one of the inhabited communities in Permude. The Kudubis are a community that is intrinsically tribal or [[adivasi]] in nature. Customs of Kudubis are like several adivasi communities of central India.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=A REPORT OF PEOPLE\u2019S AUDIT OF SEZ KARNATAKA|first=|date=|title=A REPORT OF PEOPLE\u2019S AUDIT OF SEZ KARNATAKA|url=http://www.indiaenvironmentportal.org.in/files/KarnatakaReportfinal.pdf|journal=A REPORT OF PEOPLE\u2019S AUDIT OF SEZ KARNATAKA|volume=|pages=|via=Tata Institute of Social Sciences (TISS)}}</ref> Kudubi tribal people oppose the construction of a compound wall by MSEZ.<ref>{{Cite news|last=The Hindu|first=|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Mangalore/permude-gp-stops-msez-work/article2284484.ece|title=Permude People stop construction by MSEZ|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pinto |first1=Stanley |title=The Mangalore Special Economic Zone (MSEZ) authorities have said the four acres of land in Kudubi Padavu... |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/The-Mangalore-Special-Economic-Zone-MSEZ-authorities-have-said-the-four-acres-of-land-in-Kudubi-Padavu-has-been-acquired-for-road-connectivity-to-Rehabilitation-and-Resettlement-RR-Colony-and-not-for-MSEZ-Industrial-purpose-A-release-from-SEZ-office-stated-that-the-land-was-notified-in-May-2007-and-acquired-in-March-2008-by-KIADB-at-the-time-of-Phase-I-land-acquisition-and-the-SEZ-was-given-the-possession-in-January-2010-/articleshow/7285409.cms |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=14 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Banks and financial institutes ==\n\n* [[Canara Bank]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bankifsccode.com/CANARA_BANK/KARNATAKA/DAKSHINA_KANNADA_/PERMUDE|title=Bank IFSC Code|last=Canara|first=Bank|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=The Bank Directory, Part 4|first=|date=|title=The Bank Directory, Part 4|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=WZUcAQAAMAAJ&q=Permude&dq=Permude&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwimuvPdoNToAhWOsRQKHdgFAvAQ6AEISTAE|journal=The Bank Directory, Part 4|volume=4|pages=2054|via=Accuity, 2007 - Bankers}}</ref>\n* [[Corporation Bank]]\n*[[Syndicate Bank]]-ATM\n\n== Schools and educational institute ==\n\n* Government Primary Urdu School\n\n== Religious institutes ==\n\n'''Temple'''\n\n* Shree Durgaparameshwari Temple Kateel\n* Ayyappa bajana mandir\n* Sri Saniseshwara Temple.\n\n'''Church'''\n\n*[[St. John the Baptist Church, Permude|St. John the Baptist Church, Permude.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=375844|title=Daijiworld- Independent News|last=Daijiworld|first=News|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dioceseofmangalore.com/parishes1/p/1193-permude|title=Discourse of Mangalore|last=Roman|first=Catholic|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''Mosques'''<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Muslims in Dakshina Kannada: A Historical Study Upto 1947 and Survey of Recent Developments|publisher=Green Words Publication|year=1993|isbn=|location=|pages=150}}</ref>\n\n* Jamiya Masjid\n* Minara Masjid\n*Badriya Juma Masjid.\n*Usmaniya Masjid\n\n== Transportation ==\n\n* The nearest railway station to Permude is Dokur which is located in and around 7.3 kilometer distance.\n* Mangalore railway Station is around 10.2 kilometer distance.\n* Permude's nearest airport is Mangalore International Airport situated at 5.8&nbsp;km distance.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Dakshina Kannada district]]\n\n\n{{Mangalore-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|for=Grammar, sentence structure, readability|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Permude\n| official_name                   = Permude\n| other_name                      = \n| nickname                        = \n| settlement_type                 = [[Gram panchayat]]\n| image_skyline                   = \n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Karnataka#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location of Permude in Karnataka, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|13.0015|N|74.8835|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Karnataka]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Dakshina Kannada]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[Tehsil]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Mangalore taluk|Mangalore taluk]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| leader_title1                   =\n| leader_name1                    = \n| leader_title2                   =\n| leader_name2                    = \n| unit_pref                       =  \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_total                = \n| population_metro                = \n| population_as_of                = \n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = \n| population_demonym              = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = \n| demographics1_title1            = \n| demographics1_info1             = \n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|Pincode(s)]]\n| postal_code                     = 574509.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pincode.net.in/KARNATAKA/DAKSHINA_KANNADA/P/PERMUDE|title=Postal Pincode|last=Postal|first=pincode -Permude|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n| area_code_type                  = \n| area_code                       = \n| registration_plate              = \n| blank2_name                     = \n| blank2_info                     = \n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n'''Permude''' is a village panchayat located in [[Mangalore taluk]] of [[Dakshina Kannada]] district in [[Karnataka]], [[India]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Quarterly Journal of the All-India Institute of Local Self-Government, Bombay (Volume 66) |date=1995 |publisher=The Institute |page=201 |url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=es&id=VjC2AAAAIAAJ&dq=permude+karnataka&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Permude+Mangalore+Taluka |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Kurukshetra, Volume 43, Issues 3-12|publisher=United Trade PressM|year=1984|isbn=|location=|pages=Page 114,115 &116}}</ref>Permude is derived from Perda Mudde ([[Tulu Language]]) as production of milk was plenty during early time.<ref>{{cite news |title=St John the Baptist Church, Permude to celebrate golden jubilee on Jan 13 |url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=375844 |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=[[Daijiworld Media]] |date=10 January 2016}}</ref> [[Bangalore]] is the state capital and it is located around 290.9 kilometers away from Permude.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Strengthening village democracy: proceedings of National Conference on Gram Sabha|first=|title=National institute of Rual Development, 2002|publisher=National Institute of Rural Development.|year=1999|isbn=|location=|pages=213,220}}</ref> The nearby villages surrounding Permude are [[Bajpe]] and [[Kinnigoli]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Quarterly Journal of the Local Self-Government Institute (Bombay)|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=aJmOAAAAMAAJ&q=permude&dq=permude&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjA68GA3NXoAhV2D2MBHY-4BUM4ChDoAQhVMAU|journal=Quarterly Journal of the Local Self-Government Institute (Bombay)|volume=|pages=201|via=The Institute, 1995 - Municipal government}}</ref> According to Census 2011 information the location code or village code of Permude village is 617478. The total geographical area of village is 742.43 hectares.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Special Economic Zones in India: A Study with Special Reference to Polepally|first=|title=Special Economic Zones in India:|publisher=Daanish Books|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=32}}</ref> Permude also comes under [[Mangalore Special Economic Zone]] or MSEZ.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://csez.com/rti/php/sezunit_details.php?zonecode=6&pg=u|title=List of Industries and Villages under|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Daijiworld News Portal|first=|url=https://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=109246|title=Permude GP Serves Notice to MSEZ over Illegal Construction|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Mangalore SEZ|url=http://www.itpi.org.in/uploads/journalfiles/jan4_10.pdf|journal=Towards Greater Economic|volume=India Journal 7 - 1|pages=55|via=Institute of Town Planners, India Journal 7 - 1}}</ref> Kudubis is one of the inhabited communities in Permude. The Kudubis are a community that is intrinsically tribal or [[adivasi]] in nature. Customs of Kudubis are like several adivasi communities of central India.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=A REPORT OF PEOPLE\u2019S AUDIT OF SEZ KARNATAKA|first=|date=|title=A REPORT OF PEOPLE\u2019S AUDIT OF SEZ KARNATAKA|url=http://www.indiaenvironmentportal.org.in/files/KarnatakaReportfinal.pdf|journal=A REPORT OF PEOPLE\u2019S AUDIT OF SEZ KARNATAKA|volume=|pages=|via=Tata Institute of Social Sciences (TISS)}}</ref> Kudubi tribal people oppose the construction of a compound wall by MSEZ.<ref>{{Cite news|last=The Hindu|first=|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Mangalore/permude-gp-stops-msez-work/article2284484.ece|title=Permude People stop construction by MSEZ|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pinto |first1=Stanley |title=The Mangalore Special Economic Zone (MSEZ) authorities have said the four acres of land in Kudubi Padavu... |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/The-Mangalore-Special-Economic-Zone-MSEZ-authorities-have-said-the-four-acres-of-land-in-Kudubi-Padavu-has-been-acquired-for-road-connectivity-to-Rehabilitation-and-Resettlement-RR-Colony-and-not-for-MSEZ-Industrial-purpose-A-release-from-SEZ-office-stated-that-the-land-was-notified-in-May-2007-and-acquired-in-March-2008-by-KIADB-at-the-time-of-Phase-I-land-acquisition-and-the-SEZ-was-given-the-possession-in-January-2010-/articleshow/7285409.cms |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=14 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Banks and financial institutes ==\n\n* [[Canara Bank]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bankifsccode.com/CANARA_BANK/KARNATAKA/DAKSHINA_KANNADA_/PERMUDE|title=Bank IFSC Code|last=Canara|first=Bank|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=The Bank Directory, Part 4|first=|date=|title=The Bank Directory, Part 4|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=WZUcAQAAMAAJ&q=Permude&dq=Permude&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwimuvPdoNToAhWOsRQKHdgFAvAQ6AEISTAE|journal=The Bank Directory, Part 4|volume=4|pages=2054|via=Accuity, 2007 - Bankers}}</ref>\n* [[Corporation Bank]]\n*[[Syndicate Bank]]-ATM\n\n== Schools and educational institute ==\n\n* Government Primary Urdu School\n\n== Religious institutes ==\n\n'''Temple'''\n\n* Shree Durgaparameshwari Temple Kateel\n* Ayyappa bajana mandir\n* Sri Saniseshwara Temple.\n\n'''Church'''\n\n*[[St. John the Baptist Church, Permude|St. John the Baptist Church, Permude.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=375844|title=Daijiworld- Independent News|last=Daijiworld|first=News|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dioceseofmangalore.com/parishes1/p/1193-permude|title=Discourse of Mangalore|last=Roman|first=Catholic|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''Mosques'''<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Muslims in Dakshina Kannada: A Historical Study Upto 1947 and Survey of Recent Developments|publisher=Green Words Publication|year=1993|isbn=|location=|pages=150}}</ref>\n\n* Jamiya Masjid\n* Minara Masjid\n*Badriya Juma Masjid.\n*Usmaniya Masjid\n\n== Transportation ==\n\n* The nearest railway station to Permude is Dokur which is located in and around 7.3 kilometer distance.\n* Mangalore railway Station is around 10.2 kilometer distance.\n* Permude's nearest airport is Mangalore International Airport situated at 5.8&nbsp;km distance.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Dakshina Kannada district]]\n\n\n{{Mangalore-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jake landreth", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added comma for grammatical flow", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permude"}
{"title_page": "Clyst St Mary", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=July 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|country=\t\tEngland\n|official_name=\t\tClyst St Mary\n|coordinates = {{coord|50.709274|-3.455029|display=inline,title}}\n| population=           849\n| population_ref =      (2011)\n |shire_district=\t[[East Devon]]\n|shire_county=\t\t[[Devon]]\n|region=\t\tSouth West England\n|constituency_westminster=[[East Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|East Devon]]\n|post_town=\t\t[[Exeter|EXETER]]\n|postcode_district=     EX5\n|postcode_area= \tEX\n|dial_code=\t\t01392 87\n|os_grid_reference=\tSX97369097\n }}\n\n'''Clyst St Mary''' is a small village and [[civil parish]] {{convert|3|mi|km}} east of [[Exeter]] on the main roads to [[Exmouth]] and [[Sidmouth]] in [[East Devon]]. The name comes from the [[Celtic languages|Celtic]] word clyst meaning 'clear stream'. The village is a major part of the [[electoral ward]] of Clyst Valley. At the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]] this ward population was 2,326.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/clyst-valley-e05003464#sthash.mFbx25rV.dpbs|title=Clyst Valley ward 2011|accessdate= 24 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nClyst St Mary contains [[Westpoint Arena]] and Showground, the [[Crealy Adventure Park]], the Cat and Fiddle Training Ground for [[Exeter City F.C.]] and has a small [[industrial estate]], Langdon's Business Park and a major office development.\n\nThe [[population]] has risen steadily, it was 97 in 1801, 157 in 1901 and 642 in 2004.<ref>[http://www.southwestid.org.uk/viewDataset.do?id=4149492c029155ce0102923e78fa01e0 South West ID data resource] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20070929023024/http://www.southwestid.org.uk/viewDataset.do?id=4149492c029155ce0102923e78fa01e0 |date=29 September 2007 }}</ref> This figure for the parish excludes all residents living on the north side of the main village street, who are counted within the parish of [[Sowton]], a hamlet 1 mile to the north. Both parishes are now administered collectively as [[Bishop's Clyst]], named after the Bishop's Court, former palace of the [[Bishop of Exeter]], situated between them.\n\nThe village of Clyst St Mary itself has three main areas:\n*the old village, site of the school, village hall, shop/post office and pubs;\n*the Winslade Park estate - in the grounds of the old manor house, across the [[A3052 road|A3052]], home to the majority of the population and the old church\n*the Cat and Fiddle mobile home park, {{convert|1|mi|km|1}} east of the old village.\n\nAdditionally the parish includes various outlying farms and hamlets.\n\nHistorically, the village was recorded in the [[Domesday Book]] as 'Bishop's Cliste' and is best known for its late 12th-century bridge across the [[River Clyst]], long the main route between Exeter and London. Rebuilt in 1310, it is the oldest bridge in Devon and for over seven hundred years constituted part of the main road connection between Exeter and London.\n\n==Battle of Clyst St Mary==\n[[File:Bridge over the River Clyst - geograph.org.uk - 1153029.jpg|thumb|The medieval bridge over the [[River Clyst]] at Clyst St. Mary]]\nClyst St Mary was the site of one of the decisive battles in the 1549 [[Prayer Book Rebellion]], when West Country resistance to the Protestant [[Reformation]] was quashed. After the [[Woodbury Common, Devon|Battle of Woodbury Common]] on 4 August 1549, the rebels under the control of [[Humphrey Arundell]] had re-grouped with the main contingent of 6,000 at Clyst St Mary, but on 5 August were attacked by a central force led by Sir William Francis, under the control of [[John Russell, 1st Earl of Bedford]]. After a ferocious battle Russell's troops gained the advantage leaving a thousand [[Cornwall|Cornish]] and [[Devon]]ians dead and many more taken prisoner, 900 of whom were massacred later that day at [[Clyst Heath]]. The village was burned and many of the combatants and villagers drowned in the river.<ref>[http://www.cornishworldmagazine.co.uk/content/view/77/54/1/8/ Cornish World - War of June\u2013August 1549]{{Deadlink|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>[[Philip Payton]]. (1996). \"Cornwall\". Fowey: Alexander Associates  {{ISBN| 1-899526-60-9}}.</ref>\n\n==Education==\nClyst St Mary has its own [[primary school]], Clyst St Mary Primary School,<ref>[http://www.clyststmary.devon.sch.uk/ Clyst St Mary Primary School] ''www.clyststmary.devon.sch.uk'', accessed 12 April 2020</ref> established in the 1830s. The school catchment area now includes the hamlets of Sowton and [[Farringdon, Devon|Farringdon]] as well as some neighbouring villages and many of the families of Exeter City F.C. players, who train nearby.\n\nOlder children from Clyst St Mary attend senior school at either [[Exmouth Community College]] or [[Clyst Vale Community College]] in [[Broadclyst]]. Many undertake 'A'-levels at either [[Exeter College, Exeter|Exeter College]] or Clyst Vale.\n\n==Business, commerce and employment prospects==\n\nLangdon's Business Park is the only industrialised area within Clyst St. Mary.\n\nThere is also a large office complex in Winslade Park, the site of the original manor house and, subsequently, a boarding school. The complex was initially developed by the London & Manchester group, later this site was taken over by the [[Friends Provident]] group. Apart from the refurbishment of the old school (Winslade House) in the 1980s there was a development of newer buildings on the adjacent land of Grindle House. These buildings house the Devon region [[DEFRA]] offices (in Clyst House). Winslade Park is the name for the grounds containing Winslade House, Clyst House and the other facilities here. Much of the original estate was redeveloped in the 1960s as the Winslade Park Estate.\n\n==Twin towns==\nClyst St Mary is twinned with:\n* {{Flagicon|France}} [[Merville-Franceville-Plage]], [[France]]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Clyst St Mary}}\n[[File:clyst-st-mary.jpg|thumb|Clyst St. Mary area from Donn's one inch to the mile survey of 1765.]]\n*[http://genuki.cs.ncl.ac.uk/DEV/ClystStMary/ Clyst St Mary Genealogly]\n*[http://www.clyststmary.devon.sch.uk/ Clyst St Mary Primary School]\n*[http://www.crealy.co.uk/ Crealy Adventure Park Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070531141944/http://www.devon.gov.uk/etched?url=etched%2Fixbin%2Fhixclient.exe&_IXP_=1&_IXR=110214 Devon County Councils Community Page for Clyst St Mary]\n*[http://www.clystinternet.co.uk/clyst_st_mary.html A page of information and links about Clyst St Mary]\n*[http://www.clyststmaryvillagehall.co.uk The Village Hall Official web page]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Devon]]\n[[Category:Military history of Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Cornish]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Devon]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=July 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|country=\t\tEngland\n|official_name=\t\tClyst St Mary\n|coordinates = {{coord|50.709274|-3.455029|display=inline,title}}\n| population=           849\n| population_ref =      (2011)\n |shire_district=\t[[East Devon]]\n|shire_county=\t\t[[Devon]]\n|region=\t\tSouth West England\n|constituency_westminster=[[East Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|East Devon]]\n|post_town=\t\t[[Exeter|EXETER]]\n|postcode_district=     EX5\n|postcode_area= \tEX\n|dial_code=\t\t01392 87\n|os_grid_reference=\tSX97369097\n }}\n\n'''Clyst St Mary''' is a small village and [[civil parish]] {{convert|3|mi|km}} east of [[Exeter]] on the main roads to [[Exmouth]] and [[Sidmouth]] in [[East Devon]]. The name comes from the [[Celtic languages|Celtic]] word clyst meaning 'clear stream'. The village is a major part of the [[electoral ward]] of Clyst Valley. At the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]] this ward population was 2,326.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/clyst-valley-e05003464#sthash.mFbx25r